3.2 Application Execution
Virtual Environment: Create and activate a Python virtual environment.

Bash

python -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate  # Linux/macOS
Install Dependencies: Install all necessary packages (Flask, SQLAlchemy, etc.)

Bash

pip install -r requirements.txt
Run the Application: Start the Flask server.

Bash

flask run
Access: Open your web browser and navigate to the application address (e.g., http://127.0.0.1:5000/).





4. How to Use and Run the Admin Panel
This section provides the necessary steps for reviewers and operators to launch and access the application.

4.1 Prerequisites
Ensure you have:

Python 3.x installed.

MySQL Server running locally.

All required Python dependencies installed (e.g., Flask, Flask-SQLAlchemy, Werkzeug).

4.2 Step-by-Step Execution Guide
Database Initialization:

Open MySQL Workbench (or your preferred MySQL client).

Execute the entire SQL code provided in Section 3.2. This step initializes the database ecom_admin_db and populates the crucial users, products, and orders tables.

Generate Password Hash (CRITICAL STEP):

The password hash for finalpassword123 must be generated by your Python application's security module.

Action Required: Run a Python script snippet using werkzeug.security.generate_password_hash('finalpassword123') and replace the placeholder hash in the complete_schema.sql file's Section 5a with the actual outputted hash string.

Application Startup:

Ensure all necessary Python dependencies are installed (pip install -r requirements.txt).

Run the main application file (e.g., flask run or python app.py).

Access and Login:

Open your web browser and navigate to the local application address (typically http://127.0.0.1:5000/).

You will be redirected to the login page. Use the following credentials:

Login Field

Value

Username (Email)

admin@ecom.com

Password

finalpassword123

4.3 Post-Login Navigation
Upon successful login, the administrator will be directed to the main Dashboard, featuring:

Inventory Panel: Use the menu to add new products, manage variants, and track stock levels.

Orders Panel: View Order ID 1 (which was pre-seeded as test data) to verify the order tracking features and the calculation of "Total Items" from the order_items table.

Reports: Access the custom CSV export function to generate an order report, confirming the application's ability to aggregate data across multiple tables (orders, users, order_items).